<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Functions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Functions are a fundamental building block of R: to master many of the
        more advanced techniques in this book, you need a solid foundation in
        how functions work. You've probably already created many R functions,
        and you're familiar with the basics of how they work. The focus of this
        chapter is to turn your existing, informal knowledge of functions into a
        rigorous understanding of what functions are and how they work.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-function-fundamentals">
      <title>Function fundamentals</title>

      <p>
        To understand functions in R you need to internalise two important ideas:
      </p>

      <p><ul>
        <li><p>
          Functions can be broken down into three components: arguments, body,
          and environment.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Functions are objects, just as vectors are objects.
        </p></li>
      </ul></p>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="sec-lexical-scoping">
      <title>Lexical scoping</title>

      <p>
        In <xref ref="sec-function-fundamentals"/>, we saw that every function
        has an associated environment. Now we'll explore what that means in full.
        The job of an environment is to associate, or <em>bind</em>, a set of
        names to a set of values. Environments power <em>lexical scoping</em>:
        the process of looking up the value associated with a name.
      </p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
